Oatullus’ firm and close attachment to his friends is one of the leading traits of his character. The feeling of friendship was elevated by him into devotion, demanding a complete and fervent faith on both parts, and imposing in action a circle of attentions as obligatory as religious exercises. Breach of duty was not a sentimental injury, but sacrilege 3 an unfaithful friend was not sickle, but an apostate. Such an apos- tate the Varus¹ of the preceding poem proved to be. Catullus shows in the following lines how deeply he felt the blow :—

‘ Unfaithful Alfenus, betrayer of companions so linked to- gether, has your hard heart no compassion left for your once- cherished friend? Do you not tremble to cast me off, and break your vows, like a traitor? Treachery is irreligion, and finds no favour with the gods. Despising this truth, you abandon me to my fate in a sea of troubles. What now must poor humanity do?
